 Fetching data from the network


 Recall when Figma gave us the choice to start with an iFrame-enabled widget. Although we didnâ€™t go with that option, we must still implement some of its features. Let me explain why we canâ€™t simply callÂ fetch()Â within our widget code.



 When you use a widget, you are running JavaScript code on your own computer thatâ€™s written by someone else. While all widgets are thoroughly reviewed by the Figma staff, itâ€™s still a huge security hole as we all know how muchÂ damage can be created by even one line of JavaScript.



 As a result, Figma cannot simplyÂ eval()Â any widget code written by anonymous programmers. Long story short, the team decided that the best solution was running third-party code in a closely-guarded sandbox environment. And as you might have guessed, browser APIs are unavailable in such an environment.



 But donâ€™t fret, Figmaâ€™s solution to this second problem isÂ <iframe>s. Any HTML code that we write in a file, preferably calledÂ ui.html, will have access to all browser APIs. You might be wondering how we can trigger this code from the widget, but weâ€™ll look into that later. Right now, letâ€™s jump back into code:



