 function QuotesWidget() {
   useEffect(() => {
     waitForTask(fetchData());
   });
 }



 But this will result in yet another â€œerrorâ€ where our widget will keep re-rendering with a new quote, forever. This happens becauseÂ useEffect, by definition, triggers again whenever the widgetâ€™s state changes, nay when we callÂ fetchData. And whileÂ thereâ€™s a techniqueÂ to only callÂ useEffectÂ once in React, it does not work on Figmaâ€™s implementation. From Figmaâ€™s docs:



 Because ofÂ How Widgets Run, useEffect should handle being called multiple times with the same state.



 Thankfully, thereâ€™s a simple workaround that we can take advantage of and callÂ useEffectÂ only once when the component first mounts, and itâ€™s by checking whether or not the stateâ€™s values are still empty:



