 Creating a minimal grid system


 When we focus on layouts like the â€œuniversalâ€ use case we just saw, itâ€™s tempting to think of grid areas in terms of one area per element. But it doesnâ€™t have to work like that. We can repeat idents to reserve more space for them in the layout. We saw that when we repeated the head and foot idents in the last example:



 .grid-container {
   grid-template-areas:
     "head head head"
     "left main right"
     "left main right"
     "foot foot foot";
 }



 Notice that main, left, and right are also repeated but in the block direction.



 Letâ€™s forget about full page layouts and use named grid areas on a component. Grid is just as good for component layouts as full pages!



 Hereâ€™s a pretty standard hero component that sports a row of images followed by different blocks of text:







 The HTML is pretty simple:



 <div class="hero">
   <div class="image">
     <img src="..." alt="" />
   </div>
   <div class="text">
     <!-- ... -->
   </div>
 </div>



 We could do this for a real fast stacked layout:



